Abstract (prophetic)

Cell Summary (no longer than 150 words)

The Cannabis sativa L. genome has coevolved with human culture over thousands of years as a source of food, fiber, and therapeutic compounds. The ~700 Mbp genome is organized into nine pairs of autosomes and as pair of sex chromosomes where genes are predominantly located near the ends of each chromosome. The majority of each chromosome is occupied by complete and fragmented repetitive elements occupying ~70% of the genome, a level comparable to maize. Predominant among the intact repetitive elements are Gypsy long terminal repeat elements. Within this expanse of repetitive sequences, each chromosome includes a metacentric or acrocentric chromosome.

  • Gene density
  • LTRs, gypsy
  • Cannabinoids
  • Sex chromosome
  • Terpenes
  • Disease ressistance
  • Chemotype: THCAS, THCAS:CBDAS, CBDAS, CBG, cannabinoid free
  • Chromosome/Genome length variability
  • PanGenome
    • Diversity of gene classes (cannabinoids, terpenes, disease resistance)?

nucs <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_nuccomp.csv")

nucs$GC <- rowSums( nucs[, c("C", "c", "G", "g")] )/rowSums( nucs[, c("A", "a", "C", "c", "G", "g", "T", "t")] )
nucs$GC <- nucs$GC * 100
#nucs[1:3, ]
wins <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_wins1e6.csv")
#wins <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_wins1e7.csv")
wins$CGs <- 0
for( i in unique(wins$Id) ){
  wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i] <- wins$CG[ wins$Id == i] - min(wins$CG[ wins$Id == i], na.rm = TRUE)
  wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i] <- wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i]/max(wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i], na.rm = TRUE)
}

myBed <- data.frame( chrom = nucs$Id, chromStart = 1, chromEnd = nucs$Length, gc = nucs$GC)

chrm <- sub("^.+chr" ,"", myBed$chrom)
chrm[10] <- 10
myBed <- myBed[sort.int(as.numeric(chrm), index.return = TRUE)$ix, ]

#dput(myBed$chrom)
myBed$chrom <- factor(myBed$chrom, levels = c("EH23a.chr1", "EH23a.chr2", "EH23a.chr3", "EH23a.chr4", "EH23a.chr5", "EH23a.chr6", "EH23a.chr7", "EH23a.chr8", "EH23a.chr9", "EH23a.chrX"))

myBed$gcs <- myBed$gc - min(myBed$gc)
myBed$gcs <- myBed$gcs/max(myBed$gcs)

myBed$gcs[ myBed$gcs == 0 ] <- 1

Figure 1. Genomic architecture of Cannabis sativa strain ERBxHO40_23, haplotype a. (Panel A) Circular representation of the ERBxHO40_23 haplotype A geneome. (A) Gene density, the background of each panel is colored by GC content (legend in lower left corner). (B) Density of the motif CG (also referred to as CpG, a motif associated with methylation). (C) Cannabis centromere motif density (370bp motif, blastn hits). (Panel B) Ideogram of the hemp genome. Chromosomes are named according to the CBDRx assembly (NCBI: GCF_900626175.2_cs10). Each autosomal ideogram summarized the length of 69 autosomal assemblies. The ideogram for the X chromosome summarizes the length of 65 X chromosomal assemblies. The Y chromosomal ideogram summarizes the length of 4 Y chromosomal assemblies. (Panel C) A Y chromosome panel? The strain ERBxHO40 resulted from a cross between strains ERB (type III or CBD dominant) and HO40 (type I or THC dominant; a genetically female plant (XX) that was chemically masculinized to produce pollen flowers to facilitate the cross).
